\begin_layout Problem
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

 are surfaces and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:S_{1}\rightarrow S_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma,U,W_{1})$
\end_inset

 be an r.s.p.
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(0,0)=P\in W_{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f\sigma,U,W_{2})$
\end_inset

 be an r.s.p for 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(P)\in W_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Define maps 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\sigma}:\mathbf{R}^{2}\rightarrow T_{P}S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{f\sigma}:\mathbf{R}^{2}\rightarrow T_{f(P)}S_{2}$
\end_inset

 defined respectively by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J_{\sigma}(v)=J(\sigma)\cdot v\qquad\mathrm{and}\qquad J_{f\sigma}(v)=J(f\sigma)\cdot v
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T:T_{P}S_{1}\rightarrow T_{f(P)}S_{2}$
\end_inset

 denote the tangent map of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{P}f$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{P}f=\frac{d(f\gamma)}{dt}(0)$
\end_inset

 for some curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:\mathbf{R}\rightarrow S_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
a) 
\series default
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $T=J_{f\sigma}J_{\sigma}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 be a curve on 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\sigma\circ\alpha$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:\mathbf{R}\rightarrow U\subset\mathbf{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is another curve in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(0)=\sigma^{-1}(P)$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(0)=\sigma(\alpha(0))=\sigma(\sigma^{-1}(P))=P$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\gamma}(0)=w$
\end_inset

.
 This vector is a tangent vector at 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in T_{P}S_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Take this vector and apply the tangent map 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 to it
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
T(w) & = & \frac{d(f\circ\gamma)}{dt}(0)=\frac{d(f\circ\sigma\circ\alpha)}{dt}(0)\\
 & = & J(f\sigma)\Big|_{\alpha(0)}\cdot\dot{\alpha}(0)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

using the chain rule.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $J(f\sigma)\big|_{\alpha(0)}=J(f\sigma)\big|_{\sigma^{-1}(P)}=J_{f\sigma}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $J(f\sigma)\big|_{\sigma^{-1}(P)}\cdot v$
\end_inset

 is a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{2}\rightarrow T_{f(P)}S_{2}$
\end_inset

 for some vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 This means
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T(w)=J(f\sigma)\big|_{\alpha(0)}\cdot\dot{\alpha}(0)=J_{f\sigma}(\dot{\alpha}(0))
\]

\end_inset

This matrix product makes sense becase 
\begin_inset Formula $J(f\sigma)$
\end_inset

 is a 3x2 matrix (since 
\begin_inset Formula $f\sigma:\mathbf{R}^{2}\rightarrow S_{2}\subset\mathbf{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\alpha}(0)$
\end_inset

 is a 2x1 column vector.
 The product then gives a 3x1 column vector which is the mapped tangent
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{f(P)}S_{2}$
\end_inset

 as expected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\dot{\gamma}(0)=\dot{(\sigma\circ\alpha)}=J(\sigma)\big|_{\alpha(0)}\cdot\dot{\alpha}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $J(\sigma)\big|_{\alpha(0)}=J(\sigma)\big|_{\sigma^{-1}(P)}=J_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $J(\sigma)\big|_{\sigma^{-1}(P)}\cdot v$
\end_inset

 is a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}^{2}\rightarrow T_{P}S_{1}$
\end_inset

 for some vector v.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $w=J(\sigma)\big|_{\sigma^{-1}(P)}\cdot\dot{\alpha}(0)=J_{\sigma}(\dot{\alpha}(0))$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\sigma}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 exists, whatever it may be, knowing that it isn't matrix multiplication
 by the inverse matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

, we at least know then that 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{\sigma}^{-1}(w)=J_{\sigma}^{-1}(J_{\sigma}(\dot{\alpha}(0)))=\dot{\alpha}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this into the previous expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $T(w)$
\end_inset

 we see 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T(w)=J_{f\sigma}(J_{\sigma}^{-1}(w))=(J_{f\sigma}\circ J_{\sigma}^{-1})(w)
\]

\end_inset

Or, compactly, 
\begin_inset Formula $T=J_{f\sigma}J_{\sigma}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
b) 
\series default
Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an isometry iff 
\begin_inset Formula $Tw_{1}\cdot Tw_{2}=w_{1}\cdot w_{2}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1},w_{2}\in T_{P}S_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pick some curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\sigma\circ\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, let there be another curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{2}$
\end_inset

 st.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=f\circ\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The length of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 between endpoints 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t_{0})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t_{1})$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{1}}||\dot{\gamma}||dt=\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{1}}\sqrt{\dot{\gamma}(t)\cdot\dot{\gamma}(t)}dt
\]

\end_inset

The corresponding length of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 between the same endpoints is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{1}}\sqrt{\dot{\beta}(t)\cdot\dot{\beta}(t)}dt
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=f\circ\gamma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\beta}(t)=\frac{d}{dt'}(f\circ\gamma)(t)$
\end_inset

 is the tangent map 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\gamma(t)\in S_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The integral for the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 involves constructing the tangent map at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 for each step of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

, mapping the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\gamma}(t)$
\end_inset

, and computing the integrand.
 That is 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\beta}(t)=T(w)=T(\dot{\gamma}(t))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{1}}\sqrt{\dot{\beta}(t)\cdot\dot{\beta}(t)}dt=\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{1}}\sqrt{T\dot{\gamma}(t)\cdot T\dot{\gamma}(t)}dt
\]

\end_inset

If we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $Tw_{1}\cdot Tw_{2}=w_{1}\cdot w_{2}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1},w_{2}\in T_{P}S_{1}$
\end_inset

, then, noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\gamma}(t)\in T_{P}S_{1}$
\end_inset

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $T\dot{\gamma}\cdot T\dot{\gamma}=\dot{\gamma}\cdot\dot{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 which means
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{1}}\sqrt{T\dot{\gamma}(t)\cdot T\dot{\gamma}(t)}dt=\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{1}}\sqrt{\dot{\gamma}(t)\cdot\dot{\gamma}(t)}dt
\]

\end_inset

implying that the length of a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 is preserved by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 This means 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an isometry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an isometry and that the integrals are the same.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $T\dot{\gamma}\cdot T\dot{\gamma}=\dot{\gamma}\cdot\dot{\gamma}$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}=\dot{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 we've got 
\begin_inset Formula $Tw_{1}\cdot Tw_{1}=w_{1}\cdot w_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{2}\in T_{P}S_{1}$
\end_inset

 be any other tangent vector at 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, like 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 There could be a different curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 whose tangent is 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{2}$
\end_inset

, so this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $Tw_{2}\cdot Tw_{2}=w_{2}\cdot w_{2}$
\end_inset

 as well.
 We can add these vectors together to make 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}+w_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 There could be another curve whose tangent vector is 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}+w_{2}$
\end_inset

 (indeed that curve is 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma+\delta$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{(\gamma+\delta)}=\dot{\gamma}+\dot{\delta}$
\end_inset

) so we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $T(w_{1}+w_{2})\cdot T(w_{1}+w_{2})=(w_{1}+w_{2})\cdot(w_{1}+w_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Now calculate the dot product of 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Expressing it as a quadratic form we get and using the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is linear: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
w_{1}\cdot w_{2} & = & \frac{1}{2}\Big((w_{1}+w_{2})\cdot(w_{1}+w_{2})-w_{1}\cdot w_{1}-w_{2}\cdot w_{2}\Big)\\
w_{1}\cdot w_{2} & = & \frac{1}{2}\Big(T(w_{1}+w_{2})\cdot T(w_{1}+w_{2})-Tw_{1}\cdot Tw_{1}-Tw_{2}\cdot Tw_{2}\Big)\\
w_{1}\cdot w_{2} & = & \frac{1}{2}\Big((Tw_{1}+Tw_{2})\cdot(Tw_{1}+Tw_{2})-Tw_{1}\cdot Tw_{1}-Tw_{2}\cdot Tw_{2}\Big)\\
w_{1}\cdot w_{2} & = & Tw_{1}\cdot Tw_{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Which was what we wanted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
c)
\series default
 Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an equiareal map iff 
\begin_inset Formula $||Tw_{1}\times Tw_{2}||=||w_{1}\times w_{2}||$
\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1},w_{2}\in T_{P}S_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $||Tw_{1}\times Tw_{2}||=||w_{1}\times w_{2}||$
\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1},w_{2}\in T_{P}S_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{u}(0,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{v}(0,0)$
\end_inset

 are basis vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{P}S_{1}$
\end_inset

, they are elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{P}S_{1}$
\end_inset

 and we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}=\sigma_{u}(0,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{2}=\sigma_{v}(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 will map basis vectors to basis vectors, and the corresponding basis vectors
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{f(P)}S_{2}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $(f\sigma)_{u}(0,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f\sigma)_{v}(0,0)$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $Tw_{1}=T\sigma_{u}(0,0)=(f\sigma)_{u}(0,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Tw_{2}=T\sigma_{v}(0,0)=(f\sigma)_{v}(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Letting the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{-1}(P)$
\end_inset

 vary over some region 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subseteq U$
\end_inset

 we can construct the tangent space at each point 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(R)$
\end_inset

 and, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{u}(u,v)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{v}(u,v)$
\end_inset

 as basis vectors of the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\sigma(u,v)}S_{1}$
\end_inset

, find the area of the region on 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{1}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{A}_{\sigma}(R)=\int_{R}||\sigma_{u}\times\sigma_{v}||dudv
\]

\end_inset

Since the tangent map is defined on each point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(R)$
\end_inset

, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}=\sigma_{u}(u,v)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{2}=\sigma_{v}(u,v)$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathcal{A}_{\sigma}(R) & = & \int_{R}||\sigma_{u}\times\sigma_{v}||dudv\\
 & = & \int_{R}||T\sigma_{u}\times T\sigma_{v}||dudv\\
 & = & \int_{R}||(f\sigma)_{u}\times(f\sigma)_{v}||dudv=\mathcal{A}_{f\sigma}(R)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $(f\sigma)_{u}(u,v)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f\sigma)_{v}(u,v)$
\end_inset

 are basis vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{f(\sigma(R))}S_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 preserved the area of the region, it is equiareal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There's another way to do this by doing 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{1}\times w_{2}=\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}\sigma_{u}\times\sigma_{v}....
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem

\emph on
(Lambert azimuthal equal-area projection: 1772)
\emph default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\{(x,0,z)|x\leq0\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 the plane with cartesian equation 
\begin_inset Formula $z=-1$
\end_inset

, and define a map 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell:\mathbf{S}^{2}\backslash H\rightarrow S$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(\cos\theta\sin\varphi,\sin\theta\sin\varphi,\cos\varphi)=\sqrt{2+2\cos\varphi}\Big(\cos\theta,\sin\theta,-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2+2\cos\varphi}}\Big)
\]

\end_inset

prove that the determinant of the first fundamental forms of 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}^{2}\backslash H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are equal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The surface patch of 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}^{2}\backslash H$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma(\theta,\varphi)=(\cos\theta\sin\varphi,\sin\theta\sin\varphi,\cos\varphi)
\]

\end_inset

We want to compute the first fundamental forms of both surfaces using the
 surface patches 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 for 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}^{2}\backslash H$
\end_inset


\series default
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\sigma$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sigma_{\theta} & = & (-\sin\theta\sin\varphi,\cos\theta\sin\varphi,0)\\
\sigma_{\varphi} & = & (\cos\theta\cos\varphi,\sin\theta\cos\varphi,-\sin\varphi)\\
(\ell\sigma)_{\theta} & = & \sqrt{2+2\cos\varphi}(-\sin\theta,\cos\theta,0)\\
(\ell\sigma)_{\varphi} & = & \Big(\frac{-\cos\theta\sin\varphi}{\sqrt{2+2\cos\varphi}},\frac{-\sin\theta\sin\varphi}{\sqrt{2+2\cos\varphi}},0\Big)\\
 & = & \frac{-\sin\varphi}{\sqrt{2+2\cos\varphi}}(\cos\theta,\sin\theta,0)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The first fundamental form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}^{2}\backslash H$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E_{1} & = & ||\sigma_{\theta}||=\sin^{2}\theta\sin^{2}\varphi+\cos^{2}\theta\sin^{2}\varphi=\sin^{2}\varphi\\
F_{1} & = & \sigma_{\theta}\cdot\sigma_{\varphi}=-\sin\theta\cos\theta\sin\varphi\cos\varphi+\sin\theta\cos\theta\sin\varphi\cos\varphi+0=0\\
G_{1} & = & ||\sigma_{\varphi}||=\cos^{2}\theta\cos^{2}\varphi+\sin^{2}\theta\cos^{2}\varphi+\sin^{2}\varphi=1
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and it's determinant is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{1}G_{1}-F_{1}^{2}=\sin^{2}\varphi
\]

\end_inset

The first fundamental form of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E_{2} & = & ||(\ell\sigma)_{\theta}||=2+2\cos\varphi\\
F_{2} & = & (\ell\sigma)_{\theta}\cdot(\ell\sigma)_{\varphi}=\sin\theta\cos\theta\sin\varphi-\sin\theta\cos\theta\sin\varphi=0\\
G_{2} & = & \frac{\sin^{2}\varphi\cos^{2}\theta+\sin^{2}\varphi\sin^{2}\theta}{2+2\cos\varphi}=\frac{\sin^{2}\varphi}{2+2\cos\varphi}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and it's determinant is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{2}G_{2}-F_{2}^{2}=\sin^{2}\varphi=E_{1}G_{1}-F_{1}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 were a diffeo this would imply that it is equiareal.
\end_layout

